post_text:
Keller ISD Career and Technical Education is looking for volunteers to interview students during its Mock Interview virtual sessions October 20-23.

Keller ISD CTE is looking for 150 volunteers to interview more than 850 high school CTE seniors and prepare them for future job interviews. Professionals are invited to sign-up to interview CTE students studying a variety of disciplines from audio-visual production and cosmetology, to health sciences and engineering. Even if you are not an expert in one of the CTE fields, you can have a significant impact on a student's preparation for real-life job interviews.

post_text: Keller ISD's Finance team recently received two awards, presented annually, for their continued success in financial reporting – the Certificate of Achievement for Excellence in Financial Reporting from Government Finance Officers Association (GFOA) and the Certificate of Excellence in Financial Reporting Award from the Association of School Business Officials (ASBO) for its Comprehensive Annual Financial Report (CAFR) for fiscal year ending 2019. KISD has received both of these awards for 13 consecutive years. Congratulations to our wonderful Finance Department!

Keller ISD is joining the DFW Admissions Regional Network (DARN) to host our first-ever Virtual College Fair to help prepare our students for the college application season.

The Fair will be held Tuesday, September 8, through Thursday, September 10, and include both daytime and evening offerings. Tuesday evening's presentations are entitled, "College 101" and "Paying for College." The following two evenings will feature virtual "visits" with 25-30 universities each night.

Each center will be staffed by a college, career, and military readiness coach who will help students with college and career resources such as interest inventories, college applications, financial aid information, college and technical school searches, and scholarship information. post_text:
Community Storehouse's 21st Annual Run in the Dark is going virtual this year!

Run in the Dark is a fundraising event for Community Storehouse which is an organization committed to helping Keller ISD children succeed in their education, along with children in Northwest ISD and Carroll ISD.

This year's event will feature a virtual run that participants can run at their own pace, in their own space. Run lengths will include a one-mile Fun Run or a 5K Run. Registration fees are $30 for adults and $20 for children, and the proceeds help Community Storehouse provide educational tutoring programs for low-income students and food for families in need.

post_text: Keller ISD's Board of Trustees approved a tax rate of $1.3947 per $100 property valuation for the 2020-21 fiscal year at its August 24 Regular Meeting, decreasing the rate from the previous year. The General Maintenance & Operations (M&O) rate was set at $1.0547, representing a $0.0136 reduction in the previous year's rate. The Debt Service (I&S) rate will remain unchanged at $0.34.
shared_text:
KELLERISD.NET
Board Approves Reduced Tax Rate for 2020-21
text:
Keller ISD's Board of Trustees approved a tax rate of $1.3947 per $100 property valuation for the 2020-21 fiscal year at its August 24 Regular Meeting, decreasing the rate from the previous year. The General Maintenance & Operations (M&O) rate was set at $1.0547, representing a $0.0136 reduction in the previous year's rate. The Debt Service (I&S) rate will remain unchanged at $0.34.

post_text:
Over just one month, more than 170 families donated 2,842 packages of supplies totaling just more than $5,000 for the Lone Star Pay It Forward School Supply Drive.

Lone Star PTA members and students loaded up all of the school supplies and delivered them to Western Hills on Monday, August 3. In the midst of a global pandemic and uncertain economic future, the generosity of Lone Star families ensured that Western Hills Elementary’s students will be equipped with the tools they need for a successful start to the school year.
shared_text:
Lone Star Families Pay Forward KISD's School Supply Provision
When Keller ISD announced it would be purchasing school supplies for students this year, one Lone Star Elementary School student’s generous spirit led to a school-wide service project to provide supplies to those in need.

This additional week will allow Keller ISD employees more time, prior to students entering the buildings on August 26, to plan, adapt to new safety materials and protocols, and receive training needed for the new school year.

With this change, the deadline for families to select their student’s Instructional Choice has been extended to August 12. Families can also change their selection by simply resubmitting their form. To access the form, families can consult the email they should have received on July 28, or visit www.KellerISD.net/BackToSchool/SelectionInstructions for more information.

post_text: Good luck to Bluebonnet Elementary School's Kellie Marriott and Keller Central HS's Kayla Molina as they represent Keller ISD at tonight's Region 11 Teacher of the Year Virtual Awards Ceremony!
shared_text:
2020 Teacher of the Year Virtual Award Ceremony

ESC Region 11 planned to premiere a video.
August 3 at 10:09 AM ·

Every fall, the Texas State Teacher of the Year Program honors 40 Regional Teachers of the Year, among which are two State Teachers of the Year — one in elementary education and one in secondary education — and four state finalists. These regional teachers represent each of the 20 Education Service Center regions in Texas. Find out who the Region 11 winners are tonight! This event is generously sponsored by EECU Credit Union.

post_text: As TEA’s guidance now indicates that “a blanket order closing schools does not constitute a legally issued closure order for purposes of funding solely remote instruction,” school will begin on August 19 with families able to choose whether their student(s) will attend in-person or remotely, beginning that day. We appreciate your patience as we continue to work through this new information.
shared_text:
KELLERISD.NET
New TEA Guidance Allows Parent Choice to Take Effect Aug. 19
text:
As TEA’s guidance now indicates that “a blanket order closing schools does not constitute a legally issued closure order for purposes of funding solely remote instruction,” school will begin on August 19 with families able to choose whether their student(s) will attend in-person or remotely, beginning that day. We appreciate your patience as we continue to work through this new information.

KELLERISD.NET
New TEA Guidance Allows Parent Choice to Take Effect Aug. 19

post_text: Keller ISD is aware of Tuesday’s announcement from the Texas Attorney General that provides yet another change in guidance as to who has the authority to govern the opening of schools. KISD leadership will review the ruling in its entirety, as well as additional relevant data and recommendations from health officials, before making any modifications to the plan to begin the 2020-21 school year. We will update the community as soon as possible, should any changes be made to Keller ISD’s plans.

post_text: Today, the Texas Education Agency released updated guidance regarding in-person learning for the 2020-2021 school year. Keller ISD leadership received this information at the same time it was available to the public and has not yet had the time to review or adjust its Back-to-School plans to incorporate this new information. District and campus leaders will review the updated guidance and provide information to families and staff as soon as possible.
shared_text:
Texas Education Agency
July 17 at 9:50 AM ·

PRESS RELEASE: TEA Announces Additional Reopening Guidance, Including Local Option For Online-Only Start to 2020-2021 School Year #txed

text:
Today, the Texas Education Agency released updated guidance regarding in-person learning for the 2020-2021 school year. Keller ISD leadership received this information at the same time it was available to the public and has not yet had the time to review or adjust its Back-to-School plans to incorporate this new information. District and campus leaders will review the updated guidance and provide information to families and staff as soon as possible.

post_text:
More than 2,500 employees and community members took part in the first-ever virtual Keller University Keller ISD, June 9-11.

This year's Keller University hosted 258 sessions by 229 presenters. An impressive 19,740 hours of equivalency time will be granted, and teachers averaged 10 hours of equivalency time earned. KISD was also excited to see that 271 parents joined Keller University on Thursday for Social Emotional Learning classes.

Thank you to all who worked to make this year's professional learning conference a huge success!
shared_text:

Keller University Sees Success in First Virtual Event

More than 2,500 employees and community members took part in the first-ever virtual Keller University Keller ISD, June 9-11.

This year's Keller University hosted 258 sessions by 229 presenters. An impressive 19,740 hours of equivalency time will be granted, and teachers averaged 10 hours of equivalency time earned. KISD was also excited to see that 271 parents joined Keller University on Thursday for Social Emotional Learning classes.

Thank you to all who worked to make this year's professional learning conference a huge success!

Sodexo will continue to distribute meals from 10:30 a.m.-1 p.m. every Monday and Wednesday. Beginning Wednesday, May 27, distribution will only take place at Basswood, Caprock, Friendship, Heritage, Keller-Harvel and Whitley Road Elementary Schools. Please see the link below for more information.

post_text: This year, Keller ISD Fine Arts has taken the District-Wide Art Show online with the creation of Keller ISD's first-ever KISD Student Art Gallery. The incredible pieces displayed in the online gallery include work created in school before closures due to COVID-19, as well as work created at home during the closures. Keller ISD is so proud of the students for continuing to nurture their creativity and the teachers for guiding them through their process.

post_text:
Every year, the Greater Keller Chamber of Commerce honors the Top 10 Academic Seniors from each Keller ISD high school, along with one favorite teacher who has inspired them during their educational journey. It’s a fantastic banquet each year that celebrates student academic achievement and the impact exceptional educators have on our students. While this year's event cannot be held in person, we want to celebrate these remarkable students and their amazing teachers during an online event, and ask you all to join us!

Visit www.KellerISD.net/RisingStar beginning at 6 p.m. Tuesday, May 5, and join us for this special online event, normally reserved only for the Top 10 students, their families, and their selected favorite teachers.

Keller Independent School District / Keller ISD Calendar
text:
Every year, the Greater Keller Chamber of Commerce honors the Top 10 Academic Seniors from each Keller ISD high school, along with one favorite teacher who has inspired them during their educational journey. It’s a fantastic banquet each year that celebrates student academic achievement and the impact exceptional educators have on our students. While this year's event cannot be held in person, we want to celebrate these remarkable students and their amazing teachers during an online event, and ask you all to join us!

Visit www.KellerISD.net/RisingStar beginning at 6 p.m. Tuesday, May 5, and join us for this special online event, normally reserved only for the Top 10 students, their families, and their selected favorite teachers.

KELLERISD.NET
Keller Independent School District / Keller ISD Calendar

post_text: Congratulations to the Keller High School Wind Ensemble for being invited to perform at the 74th annual Midwest International Band and Orchestra Clinic in Chicago, Illinois!
shared_text:
Keller ISD Fine Arts
April 24 at 4:16 PM ·

Keller ISD is thrilled to announce that the Keller High School Wind Ensemble has been invited to perform at the 74th annual Midwest International Band and Orchestra Clinic in Chicago, Illinois!

This is the first time in school history that this international honor has been awarded to Keller High School. The band’s application was reviewed by a panel of judges and was one of only 6 chosen from over 60 high school band applications worldwide. Considering this accomplishment alongside recent Midwest performances by the Indian Springs and Keller Middle Wind Ensembles, the KHS cluster is one of only a handful in the world where every varsity concert ensemble has been invited.

Congratulations to the members of the 2020 KHS Wind Ensemble and Mr. McGahey on this historic accomplishment!

post_text: Beginning Monday, April 13, Keller ISD’s COVID-19 closure drive-through meal pick-up will move to a two-days-per-week schedule, distributing multi-day, packaged breakfasts and lunches on Mondays and Wednesdays. Also, note that due to the Friday, April 10, District Holiday, there will be no meal distribution that day. Meals for both Thursday and Friday will be distributed Thursday, April 9.

After consulting with Tarrant County Health officials, Keller ISD is joining area school districts in extending our emergency closure. Keller ISD facilities will be closed through April 17 to help prevent the spread of COVID-19. Online learning and the Drive Through Meal program will continue.

In cooperation with our city and county officials regarding the current "stay-at-home" order, Keller ISD is asking everyone to refrain from visiting any of the District's campus playgrounds or athletics facilities. Since the District is not able to monitor gatherings of 10 people or fewer staying at least six feet apart, we are temporarily closing all playgrounds and outdoor facilities.

As you know, our schools remain closed, in an effort to mitigate the spread of COVID-19 (Coronavirus). Please visit www.KellerISD.net/Coronavirus for the latest information.

Caprock Elementary third-grader Azul Vargas was crowned the first-ever Region 11 Spanish Spelling Bee Champion at a special event held Friday, March 6 at the Region 11 Education Service Center.

As we have more specifics about what services we will be able to provide for families in need during this closure, we will communicate those directly to parents.

post_text: Due to Special Olympics Texas' decision to suspend all activities through March 31, Keller ISD's 2020 Chad Powell Memorial Special Olympics Track & Field Meet has been canceled. The meet was originally scheduled for March 17.
shared_text:
SPECIALOLYMPICS.ORG
Coronavirus outbreak: what you need to know

Special Olympics Texas
March 9 at 5:38 PM ·

Special Olympics Texas is suspending all sport training and competition activities and other activations involving our athletes through 31 March 2020, at which time the situation will be reevaluated. This includes State Basketball.

This decision was carefully made after Special Olympics International consulted with the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and after reviewing the latest guidance from the World Health Organization.

We will keep you updated on further changes. We have prepared a list of frequently asked questions that you can reference on the topic of virus prevention and control.

https://www.specialolympics.org/stories/news/coronavirus-outbreak-what-you-need-to-know

post_text:
Do you know how Casey's Kids started in 1997? Janie Casey, a former counselor in Keller ISD, discovered that a student was limiting the number of school days attended per week due to a lack of clothing, which led to her mission to find a way to fund the clothing needs of students in need across the District. Named in Janie’s honor, the Casey’s Kids Fun Run began as an effort to provide clothing and has now expanded to include other items such as school supplies and household needs.

Reminder: Sign up by March 9 to guarantee yourself a Casey's Kids T-shirt!

post_text: Revisiting more IT’S winners who are CTE teachers in Keller ISD for CTE Month. Matt Quattlebaum was a winner earlier this school year and he also happens to be Keller Center for Advanced Learning’s Teacher of the Year!
shared_text:
Keller Independent School District posted a video to playlist 2019 Videos.
September 24, 2019 at 7:45 AM ·

Our first Innovative Teachers Inspiring Students award of the 2019-20 school year goes to Matt Quattlebaum, an Engineering teacher at the Keller Center for Advanced Learning. His vision was to use the old school bus parked on campus and make it a “Skoolie,” which meant converting the bus into useable living quarters, all while generating hands-on skills practice, relationship building, and leadership opportunities for students. Interest in the project sparked quickly, and Mr. Quattlebaum and students from all over Keller ISD have turned this vision into a reality.

Keller ISD high school wrestlers competed in the Region 1-6A Wrestling Tournament on February 14-15, and three athletes walked away as Regional Champions while another eight qualified for a spot at the UIL Class 6A State Tournament.

post_text:
Power has now been restored at all campuses.

Fossil Ridge HS, Vista Ridge MS, Heritage ES, and Park Glen ES were without power due to a wider power outage that impacted more than 2,700 Oncor customers in the area. Phones and network services were also impacted at Fossil Hill MS, Chisholm Trail IS, Basswood ES, North Riverside ES, Parkview ES, Sunset Valley ES, and the Early Learning Center South.

post_text: Girls varsity basketball teams from both Keller High School and Timber Creek Talon have earned a spot in the UIL Class 6A Playoffs! Keller finished the season as District Co-Champion alongside Denton Guyer, and they will play one more time in a seeding game at 4:15 p.m. Friday, February 14, at Coppell High School to determine who will enter the playoffs as 5-6A's top seed. Timber Creek earned District 5-6A's fourth seed and will play Irving MacArthur at 7 p.m. Tuesday, February 18, in the Bi-District Round.
shared_text:
KELLERISD.NET
KHS, TCHS Girls Basketball Teams Qualify for Playoffs
text:
Girls varsity basketball teams from both Keller High School and Timber Creek Talon have earned a spot in the UIL Class 6A Playoffs! Keller finished the season as District Co-Champion alongside Denton Guyer, and they will play one more time in a seeding game at 4:15 p.m. Friday, February 14, at Coppell High School to determine who will enter the playoffs as 5-6A's top seed. Timber Creek earned District 5-6A's fourth seed and will play Irving MacArthur at 7 p.m. Tuesday, February 18, in the Bi-District Round.

First responders in the Keller ISD community are invited to enjoy a free meal at any school in the District the week of February 10-13.

Sodexo, KISD's food service provider, would like to a complimentary breakfast or lunch to first responders as a "Thank you" for their generosity and service – from their heart to yours. Local police officers, firefighters, emergency medical technicians, or district security officers are all encouraged to attend. Contact a campus for specific meal times and check in at the front office once you arrive.

post_text: We've identified an issue in which parents or guardians using certain email providers have not been receiving emails for the past week from KISD. This may impact about three percent of our parents, and our vendor is working to resolve the issue. In the meantime, families can download and log into the KISD Mobile App where any emails sent from a campus or from the district can be viewed. We apologize for the inconvenience.

Keller ISD's Board of Trustees approved the design development of the rebuilt campuses for Florence Elementary School & PTA and Heritage Elementary - Keller ISD. Since the passage of the 2019 Bond Election, the Citizens Bond Oversight Committee and groups of employees, parents, and students from both school communities have contributed feedback to the design process.

VLK Architects, Inc. provided the flyover of this preliminary design of the two new campuses.

post_text:
Independence Elementary School hosted Ability Awareness Week January 13-17, focusing on the strengths of others, and helping students understand where others are coming from and see life through their eyes.

The theme of the week was "We Are All Wonders," and focused on five different areas – physical limitations, learning disabilities, hearing impairment, communication, and visual impairment.
